You can use `sub` *to extract the last 4 words from a string* like:
```
str1 &lt;- &quot;then you must be in fact a wonderful kid&quot;
sub(&quot;.*(( *\\b\\w+){4})$&quot;, &quot;\\1&quot;, str1)
#[1] &quot;fact a wonderful kid&quot;
```
which will also work in case the string has less than 4 words.
```
str1 &lt;- &quot;then you must&quot;
sub(&quot;.*(( *\\b\\w+){4})$&quot;, &quot;\\1&quot;, str1)
#[1] &quot;then you must&quot;
```

With `stringr`, we can use `word` with arguments `start = -4` and `end = -1` to extract the four last words of the sentence:

``` r
str1 &lt;- &quot;then you must be in fact a wonderful kid&quot;

stringr::word(str1, start = -4, end = -1)
#&gt; [1] &quot;fact a wonderful kid&quot;
```

